Anonymous Wed 14 Aug 2024 18:41:35 No.68266533 Report
Quoted By: >>68267494
>>68266148
Hearing you're new to writing is why I said that in the first place. More sensory engagement can be good for the reader but you don't want to lose them either. It's the small things in moderation. For example, chapters from A'Nikke's perspective could have her noticing Thomas from the smell of baked bread on his clothes. If he touches her the texture differences between her flight feathers and body would be noticeable, and if she takes care of her beak it would be smooth while neglect would have it feel rougher. Even the crunch of a bread loaf fresh out of the oven compared to one that's rested and become softer is a minor detail that adds flavor to the story.
Anonymous
  • Post
  • Report

Anonymous Wed 14 Aug 2024 18:41:44 No.68266537 Report
Quoted By: >>68267494
>>68266148
I haven't continued with it, but I critiqued extensively on Chapter 1, so I've covered my opinion on the issue with how characters and their relevancy and motivation were introduced. (iirc I denounced having a random guy bringing gossip in and instead suggested that it start with A'nikke scouting the town early when only the bakery would be awake.)

I tend to focus on specifying the details of what I'll be using later, and avoiding describing things that won't matter later even if they would make a more "complete" picture of the scene, which seems to be what >>68263052 was trying to suggest. I trust my reader to imagine whatever scene is most interesting for him, so my objective is to ensure that what he's imagined does not conflict with what I describe later. This means I might get very specific about furniture arrangement relative to a door (because maybe who can see whom just walked in will matter) but I'll probably never describe the texture of a carpet or the color of the walls in a room.
